\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 The concept of \ldblquote family\rdblquote  was central to the rugby program\rquote s public discourses surrounding social norms of group membership. From vice-principal Jenny, through to the head coaches, and the athletes themselves, family was the metaphor most commonly used to convey the requirements of each athlete in-group. The metaphor of family contained both the solidarity and emotional support of shared membership, as well as a justification for the hierarchical structure of the group.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 Senior athlete Wang Wei offered his perspective on the family-like structure of the rugby program at the Institute:\par
{\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \li512\ri512\fi300 Its not as if there was not a lot of new stuff, because I guess at the time I was playing basketball\emdash basketball is also a team sport. But the only little bit that rugby made me experience was respect for elders, newcomers must respect senior team members, senior members must take care of junior team members, this is something that I didn\u195?\u162?\u194?\u8364?\u194?\u8482?t experience in basketball. At the time also I didn\u195?\u162?\u194?\u8364?\u194?\u8482?t understand that much, I guess China has always had respect for elders, but it didn\u195?\u162?\u194?\u8364?\u194?\u8482?t come up for me in basketball, and so then when I came to rugby my experience of it was very deep. \par
