}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi300 As a general rule, when directly addressing elder athletes, an athlete would add the suffix \ldblquote {\i ge}\rdblquote  (\u195?\u165?\u194?\u8220?\u194?\u165?) to the elder athlete\rquote s first or last name, to indicate that the elder athlete was relationally equivalent to an elder brother. When addressing Han Xiaolong, the most senior athlete in the group, for example, athletes would commonly use {\i Long Ge} (\u195?\u169?\u194?\u190?\u194?\u8482?\u195?\u165?\u194?\u8220?\u194?\u165?). When referring to the coach, on the other hand, athletes would use either the formal and respectful \ldblquote Teacher\rdblquote  ({\i Laoshi} \u195?\u168?\u194?\u8364?\u194?\u32?\u195?\u165?\u194?\u184?\u194?\u710?), \ldblquote Coach\rdblquote  ({\i jiaolian} \u195?\u166?\u194?\u8226?\u194?\u8482?\u195?\u167?\u194?\u187?\u194?\u402?), or the more colloquial suffix abbreviation of {\i dao}}. The conventions for the coach did not therefore have an explicitly familial structure, and were based more on Confucian traditions of master-apprentice relationships. When referring to a teammate in the third person, athletes would often refer to them as either their senior apprentice {\i Shige} (\u195?\u165?\u194?\u184?\u194?\u710?\u195?\u165?\u194?\u8220?\u194?\u165?) or junior apprentice {\i Shidi} \u195?\u175?\u194?\u188?\u194?\u710?\u195?\u165?\u194?\u184?\u194?\u710?\u195?\u165?\u194?\u188?\u194?\u376?), depending on whether the teammate was older or younger.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 This system of naming conventions, built around the hierarchical familial and Confucian master-apprentice relationships, is one example of the ways in which social norms of the group were modelled and reproduced. The concept of \ldblquote team\rdblquote  ({\i tuandui} \u195?\u165?\u194?\u8250?\u194?\u162?\u195?\u169?\u194?\u732?\u194?\u376?) was also highly salient in group discourse. And indeed, as per the traditional discourses that frame rugby as a character-building team sport, \ldblquote team spirit\rdblquote  ({\i tuandui jingshen} \u195?\u165?\u194?\u8250?\u194?\u162?\u195?\u169?\u194?\u732?\u194?\u376?\u195?\u167?\u194?\u178?\u194?\u190?\u195?\u167?\u194?\u165?\u194?\u382?) and \ldblquote team work\rdblquote  ({\i tuandui peihe} \u195?\u165?\u194?\u8250?\u194?\u162?\u195?\u169?\u194?\u732?\u194?\u376?\u195?\u169?\u194?\u8230?\u194?\u32?\u195?\u165?\u194?\u32?\u194?\u710?) were commonly evoked as ideal ethics of group membership. Over time, however, it became clear to me that athletes\rquote  understanding of the concept of team was closely aligned with the concept of family.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \fi300 In an official team meeting approximately two months into my first stint of fieldwork, vice principal Jenny provided the most elegant and articulate example of discursively framing the group as a family.\par
{\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs20\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \li512\ri512\fi300 ...I very much welcome everyone to join the Institute\rquote s rugby team. I also hope that in study, living, and training, everyone will treat each other like their own siblings, with mutual tolerance and understanding. I hope you are able to create a very good team atmosphere, and it is by no means easy, because everyone comes from all corners of the world. Everyone is an independent individual, more or less autonomous, prone to be relatively selfish, and may also have poor self-management skills. But this all changes when everyone comes to this big family, because rugby is a team sport. In a team sport, everyone in the team needs to be twisted together into one single rope in order for that rope to send out a force. I don\rquote t wish to see cliques of twos and threes; or to take the field with seven hearts, or five hearts\emdash rugby doesn\rquote t work like that. I wish that everyone shares only one heart. Only in this way will our team be able to achieve good results. \par
